# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cors-middleware
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In computing, **cross-origin resource sharing** (**CORS**) is a mechanism to safely bypass the same-origin policy; that is, it allows a web page to access restricted resources from a web server on a domain name different from the domain that served the web page.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A web page may freely embed cross-origin images, stylesheets, scripts, iframes, and videos.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Certain "cross-domain" HTTP requests, notably Ajax requests, are forbidden by default by the same-origin security policy.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] CORS defines a way in which a web browser and server can interact to determine whether it is safe to allow the cross-origin request.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] It allows for more freedom and functionality than purely same-origin requests, but is more secure than simply allowing all cross-origin requests.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The specification for CORS is included as part of the WHATWG's Fetch Living Standard.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] This specification describes how CORS is currently implemented in browsers.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] An earlier specification was published as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Servers can also notify clients whether "credentials" (including Cookies and HTTP Authentication data) should be sent with requests.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Suppose a user visits http://www.example.com and the page attempts a cross-origin request to fetch data from http://service.example.com.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A CORS-compatible browser will attempt to make a cross-origin request to service.example.com as follows.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A wildcard same-origin policy is appropriate when a page or API response is intended to be accessible to any code on any site.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A freely available web font on a public hosting service like Google Fonts is an example.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The value of "*" is special in that it does not allow requests to supply credentials, meaning that it does not allow HTTP authentication, client-side SSL certificates, or cookies to be sent in the cross-domain request.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Note that in the CORS architecture, the Access-Control-Allow-Origin header is being set by the external web service (*service.example.com*), not the original web application server (*www.example.com*).
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Here, *service.example.com* uses CORS to permit the browser to authorize *www.example.com* to make requests to *service.example.com*.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] If a site specifies the header "Access-Control-Allow-Credentials:true", third-party sites may be able to carry out privileged actions and retrieve sensitive information.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] When performing certain types of cross-domain Ajax requests, modern browsers that support CORS will initiate an extra "preflight" request to determine whether they have permission to perform the action.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Cross-origin requests are preflighted this way because they may have implications to user data.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The browser will then make the actual request.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] If service.example.com does not accept cross-site requests from this origin then it will respond with error to the OPTIONS request and the browser will not make the actual request.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Cross-origin support was originally proposed by Matt Oshry, Brad Porter, and Michael Bodell of Tellme Networks in March 2004 for inclusion in VoiceXML 2.1 to allow safe cross-origin data requests by VoiceXML browsers.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The mechanism was deemed general in nature and not specific to VoiceXML and was subsequently separated into an implementation NOTE.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The WebApps Working Group of the W3C with participation from the major browser vendors began to formalize the NOTE into a W3C Working Draft on track toward formal W3C Recommendation status.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In May 2006 the first W3C Working Draft was submitted.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In March 2009 the draft was renamed to "Cross-Origin Resource Sharing" and in January 2014 it was accepted as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The main advantage of JSONP was its ability to work on legacy browsers which predate CORS support (Opera Mini and Internet Explorer 9 and earlier).
[src:cors-middleware/cross-origin-resource-sharing] CORS is now supported by most modern web browsers, and can be used as a modern alternative to the JSONP pattern.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] CORS is a Node.js middleware for Express/Connect that sets CORS response headers.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] These headers tell browsers which origins can read responses from your server.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] This is a Node.js module available through the npm registry.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] See the configuration options for details.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] This module supports validating the origin dynamically using a function provided to the `origin` option.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] This function will be passed a string that is the origin (or `undefined` if the request has no origin), and a `callback` with the signature `callback(error, origin)`.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] The `origin` argument to the callback can be any value allowed for the `origin` option of the middleware, except a function.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] See the configuration options section for more information on all the possible value types.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] This function is designed to allow the dynamic loading of allowed origin(s) from a backing datasource, like a database.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] Certain CORS requests are considered 'complex' and require an initial `OPTIONS` request (called the "pre-flight request").
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] An example of a 'complex' CORS request is one that uses an HTTP verb other than GET/HEAD/POST (such as DELETE) or that uses custom headers.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] NOTE: When using this middleware as an application level middleware (for example, `app.use(cors())`), pre-flight requests are already handled for all routes.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] For APIs that require different CORS configurations for specific routes or requests, you can dynamically generate CORS options based on the incoming request.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] The `cors` middleware allows you to achieve this by passing a function instead of static options.
[src:cors-middleware/expressjs-cors] This function is called for each incoming request and must use the callback pattern to return the appropriate CORS options.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] An example of a cross-origin request: the front-end JavaScript code served from `https://domain-a.com` uses `fetch()` to make a request for `https://domain-b.com/data.json`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] For security reasons, browsers restrict cross-origin HTTP requests initiated from scripts.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] For example, `fetch()` and `XMLHttpRequest` follow the same-origin policy.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This means that a web application using those APIs can only request resources from the same origin the application was loaded from unless the response from other origins includes the right CORS headers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The CORS mechanism supports secure cross-origin requests and data transfers between browsers and servers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Browsers use CORS in APIs such as `fetch()` or `XMLHttpRequest` to mitigate the risks of cross-origin HTTP requests.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This is a general article about Cross-Origin Resource Sharing and includes a discussion of the necessary HTTP headers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The Cross-Origin Resource Sharing standard works by adding new HTTP headers that let servers describe which origins are permitted to read that information from a web browser.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Servers can also inform clients whether "credentials" (such as Cookies and HTTP Authentication) should be sent with requests.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] CORS failures result in errors but for security reasons, specifics about the error *are not available to JavaScript*.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] All the code knows is that an error occurred.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The only way to determine what specifically went wrong is to look at the browser's console for details.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Subsequent sections discuss scenarios, as well as provide a breakdown of the HTTP headers used.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] We present three scenarios that demonstrate how Cross-Origin Resource Sharing works.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] All these examples use `fetch()`, which can make cross-origin requests in any supporting browser.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Some requests don't trigger a CORS preflight.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Those are called *simple requests* from the obsolete CORS spec, though the Fetch spec (which now defines CORS) doesn't use that term.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The motivation is that the `<form>` element from HTML 4.0 (which predates cross-site `fetch()` and `XMLHttpRequest`) can submit simple requests to any origin, so anyone writing a server must already be protecting against cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Under this assumption, the server doesn't have to opt-in (by responding to a preflight request) to receive any request that looks like a form submission, since the threat of CSRF is no worse than that of form submission.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] However, the server still must opt-in using `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` to *share* the response with the script.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] No other browsers implement these extra restrictions because they're not part of the spec.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] For example, suppose web content at `https://foo.example` wishes to fetch JSON content from domain `https://bar.other`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The request header of note is `Origin`, which shows that the invocation is coming from `https://foo.example`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] In response, the server returns an `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`, which means that the resource can be accessed by **any** origin.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This pattern of the `Origin` and `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` headers is the simplest use of the access control protocol.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Unlike *simple requests*, for "preflighted" requests the browser first sends an HTTP request using the `OPTIONS` method to the resource on the other origin, in order to determine if the actual request is safe to send.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Such cross-origin requests are preflighted since they may have implications for user data.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The example above creates an XML body to send with the `POST` request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Also, a non-standard HTTP `X-PINGOTHER` request header is set.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Such headers are not part of HTTP/1.1, but are generally useful to web applications.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Since the request uses a `Content-Type` of `text/xml`, and since a custom header is set, this request is preflighted.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Let's look at the full exchange between client and server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The first block above represents the preflight request with the `OPTIONS` method.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The browser determines that it needs to send this based on the request parameters that the JavaScript code snippet above was using, so that the server can respond whether it is acceptable to send the request with the actual request parameters.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] OPTIONS is an HTTP/1.1 method that is used to determine further information from servers, and is a safe method, meaning that it can't be used to change the resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Access-Control-Request-Method` header notifies the server as part of a preflight request that when the actual request is sent, it will do so with a `POST` request method.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Access-Control-Request-Headers` header notifies the server that when the actual request is sent, it will do so with `X-PINGOTHER` and `Content-Type` custom headers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Now the server has an opportunity to determine whether it can accept a request under these conditions.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The second block above is the response that the server returns, which indicate that the request method (`POST`) and request headers (`X-PINGOTHER`) are acceptable.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The server responds with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://foo.example`, restricting access to the requesting origin domain only.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] It also responds with `Access-Control-Allow-Methods`, which says that `POST` and `GET` are valid methods to query the resource in question (this header is similar to the `Allow` response header, but used strictly within the context of access control).
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The server also sends `Access-Control-Allow-Headers` with a value of `X-PINGOTHER, Content-Type`, confirming that these are permitted headers to be used with the actual request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Like `Access-Control-Allow-Methods`, `Access-Control-Allow-Headers` is a comma-separated list of acceptable headers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Finally, `Access-Control-Max-Age` gives the value in seconds for how long the response to the preflight request can be cached without sending another preflight request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] In the present case, the max age is 86400 seconds (= 24 hours).
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Note that each browser has a maximum internal value that takes precedence when the `Access-Control-Max-Age` exceeds it.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Not all browsers currently support following redirects after a preflighted request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The CORS protocol originally required that behavior but was subsequently changed to no longer require it.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] However, not all browsers have implemented the change, and thus still exhibit the originally required behavior.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Make another request (the *real* request) using the URL you obtained from `Response.url` or `XMLHttpRequest.responseURL` in the first step.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] However, if the request is one that triggers a preflight due to the presence of the `Authorization` header in the request, you won't be able to work around the limitation using the steps above.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] And you won't be able to work around it at all unless you have control over the server the request is being made to.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The most interesting capability exposed by both `fetch()` or `XMLHttpRequest` and CORS is the ability to make "credentialed" requests that are aware of HTTP cookies and HTTP Authentication information.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] By default, in cross-origin `fetch()` or `XMLHttpRequest` calls, browsers will *not* send credentials.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] To ask for a `fetch()` request to include credentials, set the `credentials` option to `"include"`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] To ask for an `XMLHttpRequest` request to include credentials, set the `XMLHttpRequest.withCredentials` property to `true`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] In this example, content originally loaded from `https://foo.example` makes a GET request to a resource on `https://bar.other` which sets Cookies.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This code creates a `Request` object, setting the `credentials` option to `"include"` in the constructor, then passes this request into `fetch()`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Since this is a simple `GET` request, it is not preflighted but the browser will **reject** any response that does not have the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header set to `true`, and **not** make the response available to the invoking web content.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] CORS-preflight requests must never include credentials.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The *response* to a preflight request must specify `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true` to indicate that the actual request can be made with credentials.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Firefox 87 allows this non-compliant behavior to be enabled by setting the preference: `network.cors_preflight.allow_client_cert` to `true` (Firefox bug 1511151).
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Chromium-based browsers currently always send TLS client certificates in CORS preflight requests (Chrome bug 775438).
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] If a request includes a credential (most commonly a `Cookie` header) and the response includes an `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` header (that is, with the wildcard), the browser will block access to the response, and report a CORS error in the devtools console.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] But if a request does include a credential (like the `Cookie` header) and the response includes an actual origin rather than the wildcard (like, for example, `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://example.com`), then the browser will allow access to the response from the specified origin.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Also note that any `Set-Cookie` response header in a response would not set a cookie if the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` value in that response is the `*` wildcard rather an actual origin.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Note that cookies set in CORS responses are subject to normal third-party cookie policies.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] In the example above, the page is loaded from `foo.example` but the `Set-Cookie` header in the response is sent by `bar.other`, and would thus not be saved if the user's browser is configured to reject all third-party cookies.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Cookies set in CORS requests and responses are subject to normal third-party cookie policies.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Third-party cookie policies may prevent third party cookies being sent in requests, effectively stopping a site from making credentialed requests even if permitted by the third party server (using `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials`).
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The default policy differs between browsers, but may be set using the SameSite attribute.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Even if credentialed requests are allowed, a browser may be configured to reject all third-party cookies in responses.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This section lists the HTTP response headers that servers return for access control requests as defined by the Cross-Origin Resource Sharing specification.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The previous section gives an overview of these in action.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` specifies either a single origin which tells browsers to allow that origin to access the resource; or else — for requests **without** credentials — the `*` wildcard tells browsers to allow any origin to access the resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Access-Control-Expose-Headers` header adds the specified headers to the allowlist that JavaScript (such as `Response.headers`) in browsers is allowed to access.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Access-Control-Max-Age` header indicates how long the results of a preflight request can be cached.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] For an example of a preflight request, see the above examples.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `delta-seconds` parameter indicates the number of seconds the results can be cached.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header indicates whether or not the response to the request can be exposed when the `credentials` flag is true.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] When used as part of a response to a preflight request, this indicates whether or not the actual request can be made using credentials.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Note that simple `GET` requests are not preflighted, and so if a request is made for a resource with credentials, if this header is not returned with the resource, the response is ignored by the browser and not returned to web content.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Credentialed requests are discussed above.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Access-Control-Allow-Methods` header specifies the method or methods allowed when accessing the resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This is used in response to a preflight request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The conditions under which a request is preflighted are discussed above.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] An example of a preflight request is given above, including an example which sends this header to the browser.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Access-Control-Allow-Headers` header is used in response to a preflight request to indicate which HTTP headers can be used when making the actual request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This header is the server side response to the browser's `Access-Control-Request-Headers` header.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This section lists headers that clients may use when issuing HTTP requests in order to make use of the cross-origin sharing feature.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Note that these headers are set for you when making invocations to servers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Developers making cross-origin requests do not have to set any cross-origin sharing request headers programmatically.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Origin` header indicates the origin of the cross-origin access request or preflight request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The origin is a URL indicating the server from which the request is initiated.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] It does not include any path information, only the server name.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Note that in any access control request, the `Origin` header is **always** sent.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Access-Control-Request-Method` is used when issuing a preflight request to let the server know what HTTP method will be used when the actual request is made.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] Examples of this usage can be found above.
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] The `Access-Control-Request-Headers` header is used when issuing a preflight request to let the server know what HTTP headers will be used when the actual request is made (for example, by passing them as the `headers` option).
[src:cors-middleware/http-cors] This browser-side header will be answered by the complementary server-side header of `Access-Control-Allow-Headers`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] include the representation data in the body.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The following is a request with no body.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:cors-middleware/http-header] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] HTTP defines a set of **request methods** to indicate the purpose of the request and what is expected if the request is successful.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] Although they can also be nouns, these request methods are sometimes referred to as *HTTP verbs*.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] Each request method has its own semantics, but some characteristics are shared across multiple methods, specifically request methods can be safe, idempotent, or cacheable.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The `GET` method requests a representation of the specified resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] Requests using `GET` should only retrieve data and should not contain a request content.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The `HEAD` method asks for a response identical to a `GET` request, but without a response body.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The `POST` method submits an entity to the specified resource, often causing a change in state or side effects on the server.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The `PUT` method replaces all current representations of the target resource with the request content.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The `DELETE` method deletes the specified resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The `CONNECT` method establishes a tunnel to the server identified by the target resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The `OPTIONS` method describes the communication options for the target resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The `TRACE` method performs a message loop-back test along the path to the target resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The `PATCH` method applies partial modifications to a resource.
[src:cors-middleware/http-methods] The following table lists HTTP request methods and their categorization in terms of safety, cacheability, and idempotency.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] In computing, the **same-origin policy** (**SOP**) is a concept in the web application security model.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Under the policy, a web browser permits scripts contained in a first web page to access data in a second web page, but only if both web pages have the same *origin*.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] An origin is defined as a combination of URI scheme, host name, and port number.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] This policy prevents a malicious script on one page from obtaining access to sensitive data on another web page through that page's Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] This mechanism bears a particular significance for modern web applications that extensively depend on HTTPS cookies to maintain authenticated user sessions, as servers act based on the HTTP cookie information to reveal sensitive information or perform state-changing actions.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] A strict separation between content provided by unrelated sites must be maintained on the client-side to prevent the loss of data confidentiality or integrity.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy applies only to scripts.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] This means that resources such as images, CSS, and dynamically loaded scripts can be accessed across origins via the corresponding HTML tags (with fonts being a notable exception).
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Attacks take advantage of the fact that the same origin policy does not apply to HTML tags.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] There are some mechanisms available to relax the SOP; one of them is cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The concept of same-origin policy was introduced by Netscape Navigator 2.02 in 1995, shortly after the introduction of JavaScript in Netscape 2.0.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] JavaScript enabled scripting on web pages, and in particular programmatic access to the DOM.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The policy was originally designed to protect access to the DOM, but has since been broadened to protect sensitive parts of the global JavaScript object.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] All modern browsers implement some form of the same-origin policy as it is an important security cornerstone.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The algorithm used to calculate the "origin" of a URI is specified in RFC 6454, Section 4.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] For absolute URIs, the origin is the triple {scheme, host, port}.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] If the URI does not use a hierarchical element as a naming authority (see RFC 3986, Section 3.2) or if the URI is not an absolute URI, then a globally unique identifier is used.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Two resources are considered to be of the same origin if and only if all these values are exactly the same.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] To illustrate, the following table gives an overview of typical outcomes for checks against the URL "**http://www.example.com/dir/page.html**".
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Unlike other browsers, Internet Explorer does not include the port in the calculation of the origin, using the Security Zone in its place.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy protects against reusing authenticated sessions across origins.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The following example illustrates a potential security risk that could arise without the same-origin policy.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Assume that a user is visiting a banking website and doesn't log out.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Then, the user goes to another site that has malicious JavaScript code that requests data from the banking site.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Because the user is still logged in on the banking site, the malicious code could do anything the user could do on the banking site.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] For example, it could get a list of the user's last transactions, create a new transaction, etc.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] This is because, in the original spirit of a World Wide Web, browsers are required to tag along authentication details such as session cookies and platform-level kinds of the Authorization request header to the banking site based on the domain of the banking site.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The bank site owners would expect that regular browsers of users visiting the malicious site do not allow the code loaded from the malicious site access the banking session cookie or platform-level authorization.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] While it is true that JavaScript has no direct access to the banking session cookie, it could still send and receive requests to the banking site with the banking site's session cookie.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Same Origin Policy was introduced as a requirement for security-minded browsers to deny read access to responses from across origins, with the assumption that the majority of users choose to use compliant browsers.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Counteracting the abuse of the write permission requires additional CSRF protections by the target sites.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] In some circumstances, the same-origin policy is too restrictive, posing problems for large websites that use multiple subdomains.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] At first, a number of workarounds such as using the fragment identifier or the `window.name` property were used to pass data between documents residing in different domains.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Netscape Navigator briefly contained a taint checking feature.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The feature was experimentally introduced in 1997 as part of Netscape 3.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The feature was turned off by default, but if enabled by a user it would allow websites to attempt to read JavaScript properties of windows and frames belonging to a different domain.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The browser would then ask the user whether to permit the access in question.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] If two windows (or frames) contain scripts that set domain to the same value, the same-origin policy is relaxed for these two windows, and each window can interact with the other.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] For example, cooperating scripts in documents loaded from orders.example.com and catalog.example.com might set their `document.domain` properties to “example.com”, thereby making the documents appear to have the same origin and enabling each document to read properties of the other.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Setting this property implicitly sets the port to null, which most browsers will interpret differently from port 80 or even an unspecified port.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] To assure that access will be allowed by the browser, set the document.domain property of both pages.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The `document.domain` concept was introduced as part of Netscape Navigator 3, released in 1996.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The other technique for relaxing the same-origin policy is standardized under the name cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] This standard extends HTTP with a new `Origin` request header and a new `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] It allows servers to use a header to explicitly list origins that may request a file or to use a wildcard and allow a file to be requested by any site.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Browsers such as Firefox 3.5, Safari 4 and Internet Explorer 10 use this header to allow the cross-origin HTTP requests with XMLHttpRequest that would otherwise have been forbidden by the same-origin policy.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Another technique, cross-document messaging, allows a script from one page to pass textual messages to a script on another page regardless of the script origins.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Calling the postMessage() method on a Window object asynchronously fires an "onmessage" event in that window, triggering any user-defined event handlers.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] A script in one page still cannot directly access methods or variables in the other page, but they can communicate safely through this message-passing technique.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Since HTML `<script>` elements are allowed to retrieve and execute content from other domains, a page can bypass the same-origin policy and receive JSON data from a different domain by loading a resource that returns a JSONP payload.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] JSONP payloads consist of an internal JSON payload wrapped by a pre-defined function call.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] When the script resource is loaded by the browser, the designated callback function will be invoked to process the wrapped JSON payload.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Modern browsers will permit a script to connect to a WebSocket address without applying the same-origin policy.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] However, they recognize when a WebSocket URI is used, and insert an **Origin:** header into the request that indicates the origin of the script requesting the connection.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] To ensure cross-site security, the WebSocket server must verify that that origin is permitted to receive a reply.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The behavior of same-origin checks and related mechanisms is not well-defined in a number of corner cases such as for pseudo-protocols that do not have a clearly defined host name or port associated with their URLs (file:, data:, etc.).
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] This historically caused a fair number of security problems, such as the generally undesirable ability of any locally stored HTML file to access all other files on the disk, or communicate with any site on the Internet.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Lastly, certain types of attacks, such as DNS rebinding or server-side proxies, permit the host name check to be partly subverted, and make it possible for rogue web pages to directly interact with sites through addresses other than their "true", canonical origin.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The impact of such attacks is limited to very specific scenarios, since the browser still believes that it is interacting with the attacker's site, and therefore does not disclose third-party cookies or other sensitive information to the attacker.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Even when same-origin policy is in effect (without being relaxed by Cross-Origin Resource Sharing), certain cross-origin attacks can be performed.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] WebRTC can be used to find out the internal IP address of a victim.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] If attempting to connect to a cross-origin port, responses cannot be read in face of same-origin policy, but a JavaScript can still make inferences on whether the port is open or closed by checking if the onload/onerror event fires, or if we get a timeout.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] This gives opportunities for cross-origin portscanning.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Further, JavaScript snippets can use techniques like cross-site leaks to exploit long-standing information leakages in the browser to infer information cross-origin.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] These attacks can be counteracted by implementing a Cross-Origin Resource Policy (CORP) header, which allows a website owner to block cross-origin or cross-site resources, like images, videos, and stylesheets.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] CORP can also block JavaScript-initiated `fetch` requests, but only if they are sent with the `no-cors` request mode.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy does not prevent the browser from making GET, POST, OPTIONS, and TRACE requests; it only prevents the responses from being read by user code.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Therefore, if an endpoint uses one of these "safe" request methods to write information or perform an action on a user's behalf, it can be exploited by attackers.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Note that the same-origin policy does not apply to cookies for historical reasons.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] If multiple adversarial sites are deployed on the same hostname with different port numbers, contrary to the SOP, all cookies set by any of the sites are shared.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] This can be used to leak users' session tokens and steal account information.
[src:cors-middleware/same-origin-policy] Therefore, web services should be separated by differentiating subdomains rather than port numbers.
